ns were all deployed in the tumultuous presidential election of 1800-an event that nearly toppled the new republic.By illuminating this culture of honor, Freeman offers new understandings of some of the most perplexing events of early American history, including the notorious duel between Burr and Hamilton. A major reconsideration of early American politics, Affairs of Honor offers a profoundly human look at the anxieties and political realities of leaders struggling to define themselves and their role in the new nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aElite (Social sciences)xPolitical activityxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aElite (Social sciences)xPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aHonorxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aHonorxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitics and culturexHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300137798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300137798.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles